{
  "texts": [
    "They called this capacity of LLMs \"algorithmic fidelity,\" and the simulated data \"silicon samples:\" \"Our studies show that the same language model, when properly conditioned, is able to produce outputs biased both toward and against specific groups and perspectives in ways that strongly correspond with human response patterns along fine-grained demographic axes.\"",
    "Many objected.",
    "In an article directly conversing with Argyle et al. (2023), Bisbee et al. (2024) demonstrated the existence of an important divergence between LLMs' and human responses when asked to express their feelings toward certain groups.",
    "They also show that the quality of feeling thermometer prediction drops when certain variables (such as party identification and political ideology) are not provided to the model.",
    "In one large-scale experiment, computer scientists found that a mismatch between the answers of various LLMs and US respondents was the rule more than the exception, and tended to favor \"lower income, moderate, and Protestant or Roman Catholic groups\" (Santurkar et al., 2023). Similarly, von der Heyde et al. (2023) concluded from their study of LLM's answers to political questions in Germany that the model they tested leaned toward the views of certain parties."
  ]
}